metadata.name: Experimental Generative Music  #3
metadata.description: A song composed using the open source software VCV Rack. A wavy sounding synth plays unpredictable chords in scale alongside randomized drums. Kick drums repeat a different amount of times each bar. The hi hats maintain a pattern for a short period of time, but that pattern evolves and changes as time goes on. Another synth plays atop the chords changing timbre and pitch in synch with the chords.

metadata.name: Arches #35
metadata.description:
'Arches' explores the connection between a dynamic artificial structure and an algorithm that mimics the behaviour of a living organism, the Physarum slime mold.

Use your mouse to explore the scene (zooming, panning).

Press 's' to save an image.
Press 'r' to rotate the camera.
Press 'd' to show debug interface

Further you can play with the algorithm settings (shown in console):

Press 't' to increase decay
Press 'g' to decrease decay
Press 'y' to increase deposit
Press 'h' to decrease deposit
Press 'u' to increase mutation strength
Press 'j' to decrease mutation strength
Press 'i' to increase point size
Press 'k' to decrease point size
Press 'o' to increase eating
Press 'l' to decrease eating

Code licensed under NFTL 1.0. Some code has been reused from nicoptere's physarum, which is licensed under the Unlicensed license. Some of ciphrd's Microcosm work was utilized too, under special personal license from ciphrd.

metadata.name: PixlFlippr #495
metadata.description:
PixlFlippr is an offshoot of my "Simple Harmonic Motion" series, inspired by the complexity of life emerging through the interaction of simple 'dumb' behaviors, with intricate details emerging on multiple scales. PixlFlippr operates on a pixel level (in the form of a GLSL frag shader).

Every pixel oscillates at a single fixed frequency, slightly out-of-sync with its neighbors. There is no explicit pixel-neighborhood communication (as there would be in eg Cellular Automata), and every pixel acts autonomously, oblivious to its surroundings. Yet collectively, the entire system exhibits constantly evolving complex high level behavior on many scales, ranging from patterns & behaviors spanning a few pixels, all the way up to the level of the entire image. These are further amplified through the emergent pixel aliasing artefacts & moiré patterns. 

Also, it's trippy af. 

PS All generative mints are a seamless loop with a loop duration ranging from a few minutes to over an hour. So stick around & watch it mutate!

metadata.name: Southern Gothic #140
metadata.description:
“Southern Gothic” is my debut release on the fxhash platform. The project is created entirely through code. All copyrights are released to the holder of each image output, even for commercial purposes.

“Southern Gothic” borrows its name from the literary genre made famous by writers like Flannery O’Connor and Carson McCullers. Rather than illustrating a singular setting, the code generates an entire rural townscape, thereby, blurring the boundaries between representation and narrative. The individual scenes are framed frontally with an intentionally flat aesthetic character, referencing traditional folk art of the American South. The absence of human figures within these scenes adds to their overwhelming sense of darkness and forlorn. Observing multiple scenes side-by-side, one may even get the strange feeling that something terrible has happened (or is about to happen) in this rural landscape.

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.

metadata.name: EYES #227
metadata.description:
The beauty and soul of eyes have always fascinated me. There are billions of eyes in the world, all with different colors, textures and shapes and each one is still unique. With this project, I wanted to capture that natural beauty of the eyes, but also give them my unique colorful style.

Zombie and Cat eyes are more rare. Who will collect the Zombie Cat eye?

----

Created with the help of amazing cables.gl. For optimization purposes, in order to make the project load properly on fxhash, I had to use 2 textures for the eye pupil shapes instead of procedurally generating them. There is also hdr map loaded for the reflections.  

Press E to download the generated image.

----

All who collected NEBULAE were added to the reserve list. <3

metadata.name: Highrise of Homes #19
metadata.description:
Highrise of Homes project is a "vertical community" to "accommodate people's conflicting desires to enjoy the cultural advantages of an urban center, without sacrificing the private home identity and garden space associated with suburbia."

Buy a cozy cottage in our steel constructed choice lots, less than a mile above Broadway, only ten minutes by elevator. All the comforts of the country with none of its disadvantages.

[Mouse Move]
- Zoomed View.

[Mouse Click]
- Focus/Unfocus to Zoomed View.

[r]
- Random Scene.

[s]
- At Main Screen: Save with 2200x2200 px.
- At Focused Screens: Save with window size.
